**Sec. 70401. Enhancement of employer-provided child care credit.**

This section amends Section 45F of the Internal Revenue Code to increase the credit for employers who provide child care benefits to their employees. The credit percentage increases from 25% to 40% for all employers, and to 50% for "eligible small businesses" (those meeting specific gross receipts tests â€“ substituting a 5-taxable-year test instead of a 3-taxable-year test and a 5-year gross receipts limit). The maximum credit amount also increases from $500,000 to $600,000 for all employers, and $600,000 for eligible small businesses, with both amounts adjusted for inflation after 2026. Finally, it clarifies that credit can be claimed for arrangements involving third-party intermediaries and ensures jointly owned child care facilities qualify.

**Sec. 70402. Enhancement of adoption credit.**

This section modifies the adoption credit (Section 23) to make a portion of the credit refundable. Specifically, up to $5,000 of the credit will be treated as a credit allowed under Subpart C, making it refundable. It also adjusts inflation for the dollar amounts in the credit calculation, using 2001 as the base year, and clarifies that the carryforward rules apply to the non-refundable portion.

**Sec. 70403. Recognizing Indian tribal governments for purposes of determining whether a child has special needs for purposes of the adoption credit.**

This section amends Section 23 of the Internal Revenue Code to allow Indian tribal governments to be considered alongside state agencies when determining if a child has special needs for adoption credit purposes. This expands the pool of entities that can provide documentation for the credit, potentially facilitating adoptions involving Native American children.

**Sec. 70404. Enhancement of the dependent care assistance program.**

This section increases the limit on employer-provided dependent care assistance that employees can exclude from their income and employers can deduct. The limit increases from $5,000 to $7,500 for employees, and from $2,500 to $3,750 for employers.

**Sec. 70405. Enhancement of child and dependent care tax credit.**

This section modifies the calculation of the Child and Dependent Care Tax Credit (Section 21) to provide a more generous credit, particularly for lower-income families. It adjusts the "applicable percentage" used to calculate the credit, reducing the income thresholds at which the credit begins to phase out and slowing the rate of phase-out.

**Sec. 70411. Tax credit for contributions of individuals to scholarship granting organizations.**

This section creates a new tax credit (Section 25F) for individuals who contribute to scholarship granting organizations that provide scholarships to low-income students for elementary and secondary education. The credit is limited to $1,700 and is reduced by any state credit. The organizations must meet specific requirements, including spending a minimum percentage of contributions on scholarships and not co-mingling funds.

**Sec. 70412. Exclusion for employer payments of student loans.**

This section makes the exclusion for employer payments of student loans permanent. Previously set to expire, the exclusion allows employers to pay up to $10,000 per employee per year toward student loans without the employee having to include it as income, and increases that amount to $7,500. It also adjusts the amount for inflation after 2026.

**Sec. 70413. Additional expenses treated as qualified higher education expenses for purposes of 529 accounts.**

This section expands the types of expenses that can be used from 529 accounts. It now includes tuition, fees, books, supplies, and equipment for elementary and secondary education, as well as tutoring, standardized testing fees, dual enrollment costs, and certain educational therapies for students with disabilities. It also increases the annual contribution limit to $20,000.

**Sec. 70414. Certain postsecondary credentialing expenses treated as qualified higher education expenses for purposes of 529 accounts.**

This section further expands 529 account usage by allowing funds to be used for postsecondary credentialing expenses, such as vocational training and certifications. The expenses must be related to programs listed on state or federal databases and lead to recognized credentials.

**Sec. 70415. Modification of excise tax on investment income of certain private colleges and universities.**

This section modifies the excise tax on investment income of private colleges and universities (Section 4968). It adjusts the tax rates based on endowment size, increasing the thresholds and rates. It also adds new rules regarding net investment income, including treatment of student loan interest and federally subsidized royalty income.

**Sec. 70416. Expanding application of tax on excess compensation within tax-exempt organizations.**

This section expands the application of the tax on excess compensation paid to employees of tax-exempt organizations (Section 4960). It removes the sunset provision, meaning the tax applies to compensation paid after December 31, 2016, regardless of when the employee was hired.

**Sec. 70421. Permanent renewal and enhancement of opportunity zones.**

This section makes the Opportunity Zone program permanent and makes several changes. It extends the designation period, adjusts the criteria for designating low-income communities, and modifies the rules for capital gains invested in Opportunity Zone property, including a new "qualified rural opportunity fund" designation.

**Sec. 70422. Permanent enhancement of low-income housing tax credit.**

This section makes permanent the increased state housing credit ceiling for the Low-Income Housing Tax Credit. It also modifies the rules regarding tax-exempt bond financing to provide more flexibility for developers.

**Sec. 70423. Permanent extension of new markets tax credit.**

This section permanently extends the New Markets Tax Credit, which incentivizes investments in low-income communities.

**Sec. 70424. Permanent and expanded reinstatement of partial deduction for charitable contributions of individuals who do not elect to itemize.**

This section makes permanent and increases the partial deduction for charitable contributions for individuals who do not itemize deductions. The deduction increases from $300/$600 (single/married) to $1,000/$2,000.

**Sec. 70425. 0.5 percent floor on deduction of contributions made by individuals.**

This section introduces a 0.5% floor on charitable contributions for individuals, meaning they must contribute more than 0.5% of their contribution base before they can deduct the excess. It also establishes rules for carrying forward disallowed contributions.

**Sec. 70426. 1-percent floor on deduction of charitable contributions made by corporations.**

This section introduces a 1% floor on charitable contributions for corporations, meaning they must contribute more than 1% of their taxable income before they can deduct the excess. It also establishes rules for carrying forward disallowed contributions.

**Sec. 70427. Permanent increase in limitation on cover over of tax on distilled spirits.**

This section permanently increases the limitation on the cover-over of tax on distilled spirits.

**Sec. 70428. Nonprofit community development activities in remote native villages.**

This section clarifies that nonprofit community development activities in remote Native villages are considered substantially related to the organization's exempt purpose, and provides for certain transfers of assets to such organizations.

**Sec. 70429. Adjustment of charitable deduction for certain expenses incurred in support of Native Alaskan subsistence whaling.**

This section increases the limit on the charitable deduction for expenses incurred in support of Native Alaskan subsistence whaling.

**Sec. 70430. Exception to percentage of completion method of accounting for certain residential construction contracts.**

This section modifies the rules regarding the percentage of completion method of accounting for residential construction contracts, providing more flexibility for contractors.

**Sec. 70431. Expansion of qualified small business stock gain exclusion.**

This section expands the exclusion for gains from the sale of qualified small business stock. It phases in a 100% exclusion over a 5-year period and increases the per-issuer limit for gains.

**Sec. 70432. Repeal of revision to de minimis rules for third party network transactions.**

This section restores the previous de minimis rules for third-party network transactions, requiring reporting only when transactions exceed $20,000 and 200 transactions.

**Sec. 70433. Increase in threshold for requiring information reporting with respect to certain payees.**

This section increases the threshold for requiring information reporting on payments to payees from $600 to $2,000.

**Sec. 70434. Treatment of certain qualified sound recording productions.**

This section extends tax benefits to qualified sound recording productions, allowing them to be treated similarly to qualified film and television productions for purposes of the production tax credit.

**Sec. 70435. Exclusion of interest on loans secured by rural or agricultural real property.**

This section creates a new exclusion allowing a portion of the interest income from loans secured by rural or agricultural real property to be excluded from gross income.

**Sec. 70436. Reduction of transfer and manufacturing taxes for certain devices.**

This section reduces the transfer and manufacturing taxes on firearms.

**Sec. 70437. Treatment of capital gains from the sale of certain farmland property.**

This section provides a special rule for the taxation of capital gains from the sale of qualified farmland property, allowing taxpayers to elect to pay the tax in installments.

**Sec. 70438. Extension of rules for treatment of certain disaster-related personal casualty losses.**

This section extends the rules for treating certain disaster-related personal casualty losses.

**Sec. 70439. Restoration of taxable REIT subsidiary asset test.**

This section restores the asset test for taxable REIT subsidiaries.

